TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Social Capital Theory of Career Success
AU  - Seibert, Scott E.
AU  - Kraimer, Maria L.
AU  - Liden, Robert C.
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069452
DO  - 10.5465/3069452
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 219
EP  - 237
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A model integrating competing theories of social capital with research on career success was developed and tested in a sample of 448 employees with various occupations and organizations. Social capital was conceptualized in terms of network structure and social resources. Results of structural equation modeling showed that network structure was related to social resources and that the effects of social resources on career success were fully mediated by three network benefits: access to information, access to resources, and career sponsorship.
AB  - A model integrating competing theories of social capital with research on career success was developed and tested in a sample of 448 employees with various occupations and organizations. Social capital was conceptualized in terms of network structure and social resources. Results of structural equation modeling showed that network structure was related to social resources and that the effects of social resources on career success were fully mediated by three network benefits: access to information, access to resources, and career sponsorship.
