T1  - Knowledge Representations and Knowledge Transfer
AU  - Boland, Richard J.
AU  - Singh, Jagdip
AU  - Salipante, Paul
AU  - Aram, John D.
AU  - Fay, Sharon Y.
AU  - Kanawattanachai, Prasert
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069463
DO  - 10.5465/3069463
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 393
EP  - 417
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Cognitive and learning theories were used to develop a framework in which different knowledge representations prime recipients with different schemata and thereby differentially affect their decision making. The authors evaluated interpretive, general, and particular knowledge representations in a laboratory experiment with managers. The hypotheses received mixed support, with significant results indicating the importance of particular knowledge representations in managerial decision making and an intriguing role for interpretive knowledge representations.
