TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Dynamic Nature of Conflict: A Longitudinal Study of Intragroup Conflict and Group Performance
AU  - Jehn, Karen A.
AU  - Mannix, Elizabeth A.
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069453
DO  - 10.5465/3069453
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 238
EP  - 251
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In a longitudinal study, we found that higher group performance was associated with a particular pattern of conflict. Teams performing well were characterized by low but increasing levels of process conflict, low levels of relationship conflict, with a rise near project deadlines, and moderate levels of task conflict at the midpoint of group interaction. The members of teams with this ideal conflict profile had similar pre- established value systems, high levels of trust and respect, and open discussion norms around conflict during the middle stages of their interaction.
AB  - In a longitudinal study, we found that higher group performance was associated with a particular pattern of conflict. Teams performing well were characterized by low but increasing levels of process conflict, low levels of relationship conflict, with a rise near project deadlines, and moderate levels of task conflict at the midpoint of group interaction. The members of teams with this ideal conflict profile had similar pre- established value systems, high levels of trust and respect, and open discussion norms around conflict during the middle stages of their interaction.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069453
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069453
Y2  - 2026/04/24
