TY  - JOUR
T1  - Social Networks and the Performance of Individuals and Groups
AU  - Sparrowe, Raymond T.
AU  - Liden, Robert C.
AU  - Wayne, Sandy J.
AU  - Kraimer, Maria L.
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069458
DO  - 10.5465/3069458
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 316
EP  - 325
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - A field study involving 190 employees in 38 work groups representing five diverse organizations provided evidence that social networks, as defined in terms of both positive and negative relations, are related to both individual and group performance. As hypothesized, individual job performance was positively related to centrality in advice networks and negatively related to centrality in hindrance networks composed of relationships tending to thwart task behaviors. Hindrance network density was significantly and negatively related to group performance.
AB  - A field study involving 190 employees in 38 work groups representing five diverse organizations provided evidence that social networks, as defined in terms of both positive and negative relations, are related to both individual and group performance. As hypothesized, individual job performance was positively related to centrality in advice networks and negatively related to centrality in hindrance networks composed of relationships tending to thwart task behaviors. Hindrance network density was significantly and negatively related to group performance.
