TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Science and Practice of Team Development: Improving the Link
AU  - Offermann, Lynn R.
AU  - Spiros, Rebecca K.
Y1  - 2001/04/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069462
DO  - 10.5465/3069462
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 376
EP  - 392
VL  - 44
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Qualitative and quantitative data from team development practitioners were used to examine the link between the science and the practice of team development. Differences between academic and full-time practitioners were found in the value placed on empirical knowledge sources. Familiarity with recent relevant literature was associated with better intervention outcomes, and practitioners who valued empirical outlets reported greater short-term success than those who did not. Suggestions for improving the integration of science and practice with teams are presented.
AB  - Qualitative and quantitative data from team development practitioners were used to examine the link between the science and the practice of team development. Differences between academic and full-time practitioners were found in the value placed on empirical knowledge sources. Familiarity with recent relevant literature was associated with better intervention outcomes, and practitioners who valued empirical outlets reported greater short-term success than those who did not. Suggestions for improving the integration of science and practice with teams are presented.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069462
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069462
Y2  - 2026/04/24
